Case Study Unit #10: Imputations¶

By: Armando Vela & Jeff Washburn

Date: 11/3/2020

Abstract¶

Machine learning models require a good dataset. Whenever a dataset has missing or impure data, then decisions need to be made on how to handle the dataset. Missing data can be categorized into 3 different types:

  • Missing Completely at Random (MCAR)
    • Completely random missing data, cannot explain why
    • Example: Power outage causing various data to be missing
  • Missing at Random (MAR)
    • Can find a pattern in which data is missing
    • Only missing in subset of data
    • Example: Car data - when make is Ford, data is missing
    • More common
  • Missing Not at Random (MNAR)
    • You can tell definite pattern as why data is missing
    • Can 100% predict when data is missing
    • Example: Car data - when make is Ford, engine displacement is missing
    • Not very common

Once missing data is identified, then one must choose on how to handle that missing data. For example one could:

  • Listwise Deletion: Drop the row if any missing data
  • Pairwise Deletion: Say for example a case contains 3 variables: VAR1, VAR2, and VAR3. A case may have a missing value for VAR1, but this does not prevent some statistical procedures from using the same case to analyze variables VAR2 and VAR3
  • Single Imputation: missing value is replaced by a value using for example: mean/median/mode, dummy variable, regression substition, hot deck imputation, last value carried forward
  • Multiple Imputation: allow for the uncertainty about the missing data by creating several different plausible imputed data sets and appropriately combining results obtained from each of them

Lastly, once the strategy of handling missing data is executed, then use the data to create a model

Introduction¶

Within this case study, we had to impute the missing values within the Sberbank Russian Housing Market dataset and run a machine learning model on the imputed dataframe. Additional information on how we identified missing values, dealt with anomolies, imputed NAs, and ran machine learning models can be found within the Methods section. Lastly, since our main focus for this study was imputations, we elected to use the 'pycaret' machine learning package to quickly run a large number of different regression algorithms on the same dataset.

A regression model was used to predict the housing prices for the Sberbank Russian Housing Market. Four dataframes were created each with different methods of imputations to address missing values. After running machine learning models on each, it was identified that the dataframe imputated using an interative Bayesian Ridge Regression approach provided the best R^2 score and Root Mean Squared Logarithmic Error (RMSLE) score.

Methods¶

The approach we took on this dataset was as follows:

  1. Identify the missing data (see Figure 1)
  2. Impute values based on pattern of how data was missing (see Figure 2). The data appears to be MAR for certain groups of data. Because of this, we approached imputation by creating 4 different dataframes using different methodology for imputing the values using single and multiple imputation methods:
    • Simple Imputation using Mean:
      • Method: The mean is calculated for each column and the resulting amount replaces each NA value within the associated column. Note, the imputation is simple since it only goes through the data once.
    • Simple Imputation using Median:
      • Method: The median is calculated for each column and the resulting amount replaces each NA value within the associated column. Note, the imputation is simple since it only goes through the data once.
    • Iterative Imputation Using Bayesian Ridge Regression:
      • Method: The imputation is iterative since it passes over the data multiple times. For our instance, we used 5 iterations. Also, the initial strategy uses median values so that the Bayesian Ridge Regression can run through the model without errors.
    • Iterative Imputation using Decision Trees Regression:
      • Method: The imputation is iterative since it passes over the data multiple times. For our instance, we used 5 iterations. Also, the initial strategy uses median values so that the Decision Trees Regression can run through the model without errors.
  3. Deal with anomalies. This includes handling outliers, and for example build years that do not fall in range.
  4. Use pycaret to test a variety of models against each of the imputed data sets from step 2 above
  5. Compare model performance to find best performing model against the imputed data sets.
  6. Tune hyperparameters on best performing model found from step 5 above to improve model performance.

The following features seemed odd to have a 0 within them. We made them NA so that they can be imputed by our methods.

  • full_sq
  • life_sq
  • floor
  • max_floor

Missing Values Imputations¶

Since such a large number of columns had NA values, we decided to experiment with using different imputation methods and compare results based on the R2 and RMSLE scores provided by our regression models. Also, since it looks like the items missing were missing at random and not missing completely at random, we felt deletion methods should not be used on this dataset.

With that said, we used the cleaned dataframe from above and imputed the missing values using the following imputation methods. Code details can be found within Appendix.

  • Simple Imputation using Mean
  • Simple Imputation using Median
  • Iterative Imputation Using Bayesian Ridge Regression
  • Iterative Imputation using Decision Trees Regression

Run Machine Learning Model¶

Once all missing values were imputed, we ran each dataframe using the pycaret module with the following techniques included:

  • Normalization
  • Feature Selection
  • Remove MultiCollinearity

Additional code details can be found within the appendix below.

Figure 7: Example of PyCaret Output Displaying all Regression Models ran on iterative Bayesian Ridge Dataframe

Results¶

After running each dataframe using the pycaret machine learning module, we were able to identify that the Iterative Bayesisan Ridge (BR) imputated dataframe provided the best R2 and RMSLE scores. Furthermore, it was also identified that the catboost regressor algorithm provided the best regression scores for each of the dataframes.

See figure below displaying the scores for each model.

Figure 9: Tuned Model Using Iterative BR Dataframe

Conclusion¶

As a result of this case study, we are confident in stating that how missing data is imputed can directly affect overall results. Furthermore, dropping NAs wouldnt have been a viable option since it would have eliminated more than two-thirds of the overall dataset. Finally, we can still improve the performance of our model by continuing to tune hyperparameters or conduct feature engineering within the dataset.

Create helpful functions¶

In [10]:
def identifyNA(dataframe):
    """
    Purpose: To identify NA Count within each column of dataframe.
    Returns: A dataframe with column Title, NA Count, Total Count, and Ratio
    """
    retDf = pd.DataFrame(columns=['ColumnTitle', 'NA_Count', 'Total_Count', 'Ratio', 'VariableType'])
    columnList = dataframe.columns
    
    for idx in range(len(columnList)):
        column = columnList[idx]
        NA_Count = dataframe[column].isnull().sum()
        Total_Count = len(dataframe[column])
        Ratio = round(NA_Count / Total_Count, 2)
        VariableType = dataframe.dtypes[idx]
        
        retDf.loc[idx] = [column, NA_Count, Total_Count, Ratio, VariableType]
        
    return(retDf)

Iterative Imputer Example¶

Since missing values are only within numeric columns. Filter for only numeric columns to impute.¶

In [61]:
#Get entire dataset and filter for only numeric columns
df_Num = cleanDf.select_dtypes(include=[np.number])
df_cat = cleanDf.select_dtypes(exclude=[np.number])
In [62]:
def imputeNA(dataframe, complexity, method):
    """
    Purpose: To impute NAs within each column of dataframe.
    Complexity: Simple or Iterative
    Methods for Simple Complexity: 'mean', 'median', 'most_frequent', 'constant'
    Methods for Iterative Complexity: BR, DTR, ETR, KNR
    Returns: A dataframe
    """
    
    if (complexity == 'Simple'):
        
        si = SimpleImputer(missing_values=np.nan, strategy=method)
        retDf = si.fit_transform(dataframe)
    
    elif (complexity == 'Iterative'):
        
        if (method == 'DTR'):
            impute_estimator = DecisionTreeRegressor(max_features='sqrt', random_state=0)
        elif (method == 'ETR'):
            impute_estimator = ExtraTreesRegressor(n_estimators=10, random_state=0)
        elif (method == 'KNR'):
            impute_estimator = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=15)
        elif (method == 'BR'):
            impute_estimator = BayesianRidge()
        
                
        imputer = IterativeImputer(estimator=impute_estimator,
                                   missing_values = np.nan,
                                   max_iter=5, 
                                   random_state=0, 
                                   verbose=0,    
                                   initial_strategy='median')
        retDf = imputer.fit_transform(dataframe)
        
    columnNames = list(dataframe)
    retDf = pd.DataFrame(retDf, columns=columnNames)
    return(retDf)
